alliance, thus rethinking the very foundations of modern militarism. She interrogates how essentialist notions of both childhood and war have been productively intertwined; how assumptions about childhood and war have converged; and how children and childhood have worked as symbolic constructions and powerful rhetorical tools, particularly in the decades between the nation- and empire-building efforts of the late-nineteenth and early twentieth centuries up to the uneven manifestations of globalization at the beginning of the twenty-first.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChildren and warzJapanxHistory. 0aChildren and warzJapan. 0aMilitarismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aWarxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  achild labor.  achild military.  achildhood.  achildren.  aexploiting children.  aglobalization.  ahistory of children and war.  ahistory of children.  ainnocence.  ajapan.  alate 19th century.  amodern conceptions of war.  amodern militarism.  anaturalizing war.  apeace.  arhetorical tools.  asymbolic constructions.  avulnerability.  awhat it means to be human.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029544540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096823340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968233/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles